
* Implement DataStore & CRL in terms of BufferedConsistentRocksDB
    * Should be pretty easy to load CRL content. Just add a visit_all method that applies a function to each key/value pair
    * deletion of non-existent keys isnt an error. May be able to use this to simplify state handling (delete all keys that *could* be associated with a tx)

* Useful
   - RocksDB store (there is a java wrapper)
      - keep all objects in RAM (** this is just an option. Can do the queries via RocksDB api as well **)
      - use key-value DB for backing store
         - Write performance wont be as good as possible but we can ignore a huge number of issues
         - Use a WriteBatch to aggregate all changes while a commit is outstanding then immediately do another commit if next batch isn't empty
   - RocksDB for CRL
      - similar batched-commit strategy
      - Use a write-batch to aggregate all changes while synchronous commit is outstanding
      - Could use this to simplify file-store impl. Write impending changes here so they can be re-done on crash.
   - very basic error handling
      - read driver
      - transaction driver
   - offline store transfer
      - get this for free if we simply don't do error recovery
         - or only do client-driven error recovery
         - repair only objects that are seen to be defective during a read operation
         **** Could use this for a simple scan-like rebuild process. Have a background task constantly walking the allocation trees and fetching object state (not data)
         **** When errors are seen, repair them.
         **** No need for error logging. 
         ****** Gossip-based error recovery for in-mem stores. Periodically gossip about object version/refcount with nearby stores.
         ****** Mask based error recovery for in-mem stores. With each object, keep a bitmask of peer stores. set ones for all stores seen to have accepted the latest value
                 *** This is probably the easiest proactive rebuild mechanism
                 *** TxDriver should send a TxResult message with minimum-set of known-good recipients
                 *** Also eliminates need to delay, "late" Tx messages are valid for updating bitmask if version/refcount match
   - Live transfer between nodes
       * ideally not needing to offline the store
       * Ownership transfers instantaneously (via commit). Use log + in-mem copies of all modified objects while download of read-only store state is in progress

* Will need a StorageNode class. This wraps data stores on a single machine.
   - Has an IP:port for network connections
   - Maintains zmq network
   - Implements message send/receive
   - Has DataStores, CRL, TransactionManager (from local config file)
   - Has a System instance for interfacing with the rest of the system
   
 * Will need an AspenSystem implementation.
    * Implements a Client
    * Identified by a generated UUID
        - Set this as ZMQ socket identity
        - Use this as the Array[Byte] for Client messenger identity
        - StorageNodes use Router socket so they know where to send replies
    * Bootstraps from a config file that defines Map[NetworkEndpoint, List[data-store-id]]
  
  
Figure out the allocation/bootstrapping issues

* Core package is message-handling centric.
  * only generated messages are in response to other messages
      |-> TransactionDriver subclasses are the only classes that generate messages and these will still
          generally only be responses. The only truly "generated" messages are from Paxos error recovery
          e.g. lost messages, leadership collisions, etc
          
  * Transaction, Allocation, & Read are all implemented with Managers and Drivers. Each operation gets a
    UUID and a driver instance drives the operation to completion.
          
  * network.MessageReceiver instance
     - dispatches messages to appropriate store.TransactionManager
         - dispatches to appropriate Transaction/TransactionDriver
  
* Transaction
   - Fills the Acceptor & Learner Paxos roles
   - Interacts with a DataStore to vote on whether or not a transaction should be committed
   - Interacts with the CrashRecovery Handler to ensure transaction state is not lost
   - Locks the object(s) to the Transaction if voting for commit
   - Ensures DataStore can CRL state is cleaned up when the transaction completes
    
* TransactionDriver
   - Fills Proposer & Learner roles Paxos.
   - Receives TxPrepared, TxAccepted and sends Prepare/Accept msgs
   - Created for designatedLeader nodes
   - Created for recovery of Tx with failed leader
   - Create via factory object passed to TxManager
   - Totally encapsulates the retransmit/retry logic
   		

  
* How to handle the data?
  * Want to allow it to live off-heap
  * No need to split it up in memory
  * LocalUpdates could be a BufferPointer,
      * Constructor reads buffer header to generate: List[(DataUpdateIndex,BufferOffset,Length)]
      
Mid-Term Enhancements:
* Add support for PrepareResponse messages received before corresponding Prepare message
      
      
BackLog
* Add store-side failed allocation detection and recovery

* Add detection & handling of leader failure

* Add detection and handling for Transaction recovery
   - While Tx is still in progress
   - After Tx commit/abort
   - After one or more objects have been updated *after* the Tx committed/aborted

* Add special messages for "PartiallyAccepted" and "SuccessfullyCommitted"
   |-> Use these in lieu of the normal messages if the crash recovery log is down. Peers use these to avoid
       adding recovery entries for transactions successfully processed.